WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
6-0 English

2
00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:05.000
From BBCLearningEnglish.com

3
00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Hello, this is 6-minute English from BBCLearningEnglish. I'm Neil

4
00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:17.000
And I'm Georgie, do you live in a neat and tidy home? Or is there stuff everywhere?

5
00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:23.000
If your room is filled with heaps of clothes and piles of books, you may have a problem with clutter.

6
00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:28.000
Things in your home which take up space in an untidy disorganised way.

7
00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:36.000
Clutter is a common problem. In fact, clutter was the topic of a recent episode of BBC Radio 4 program Woman's Hour.

8
00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:40.000
Here's presenter, Nula McGuven, reading a message from one listener.

9
00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:46.000
Some of you have been in touch already to share your thoughts and experiences when it comes to clutter.

10
00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:53.000
Here is one. The clutter in my house is actually starting to affect my mental health. I can't think or work anymore.

11
00:00:53.000 --> 00:01:01.000
So much so, it woke me 4 a.m. this morning and I felt a strong urge to tidy. I have given myself a week as I cannot take it anymore.

12
00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:05.000
So, Neil, do you have a problem with clutter?

13
00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:11.000
Well, I don't have a problem with clutter, but I live with children and there is clutter everywhere.

14
00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:13.000
And it drives me mad.

15
00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:15.000
Oh, that's so annoying.

16
00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:16.000
How about you?

17
00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:22.000
Yeah, I don't have a problem with clutter. I would describe myself as a minimalist. I don't have very much stuff.

18
00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:24.000
Ah, very efficient.

19
00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:25.000
Yes.

20
00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:30.000
So, we don't have a problem with clutter, but if you do, there's a simple solution.

21
00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:34.000
D-cluttering, or throwing away some of the unused stuff filling our homes.

22
00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:38.000
But deciding what to keep and what to throw away is not so easy.

23
00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:45.000
So, in this episode, we'll hear some advice on keeping your life clutter free along with some useful new words and phrases.

24
00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:51.000
And remember, you can find all the vocabulary for this program along with a quiz and worksheet on our website.

25
00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:54.000
BBCLearningEnglish.com.

26
00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:57.000
But first, I have a question for you, Georgie.

27
00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:04.000
Decluttering was popularised by Mary Condos best selling 2011 book The Life Changing Magic of Tideying Up.

28
00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:06.000
And there's still lots of interest today.

29
00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:12.000
So, how many Instagram posts can you currently find under the hashtag Declutter?

30
00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:19.000
Is it A, 2.6000, B, 2.6 million, or C 26 million?

31
00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:24.000
I'm going to go in the middle and say, B, 2.6 million.

32
00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:27.000
Okay, we'll find out the answer at the end of the program.

33
00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:36.000
As well as social media, decluttering has become popular with television shows, including the BBC's interior design masters.

34
00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:44.000
Here, one of the show's judges, Michelle Agunder-Hin, tells BBC Radio Force Woman's hour why she thinks clutter is such a problem.

35
00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:48.000
Visual clutter is more exhausting than we realise.

36
00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:52.000
It's not just stuff. Our brains are constantly processing our surroundings.

37
00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:56.000
So, they have to work overtime if they're surrounded by chaos.

38
00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:00.000
So, if you feel drained or exhausted at home, it could be your clutter.

39
00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:04.000
I mean, we know that homily, clear space, clear mind.

40
00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:13.000
And I promise you that when you clear away the stuff that has no purpose in your life, you will feel better, lighter, uplifted, energized.

41
00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:22.000
In a cluttered room, our brains work overtime, meaning they work extra hard to make sense at the disorder, leaving us exhausted.

42
00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:27.000
Work overtime also often means work longer than your set hours.

43
00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:32.000
Getting rid of clutter makes us feel uplifted, cheerful, happy and more positive.

44
00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:38.000
It sounds simple, doesn't it? And there's even an expression in English, clear space, clear mind.

45
00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:43.000
So, why do many of us find it hard to throw stuff away, even things we rarely use?

46
00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:47.000
One reason people put off decluttering is the time it takes.

47
00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:52.000
Plus, it can be emotionally disturbing deciding what to keep and what to throw away.

48
00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:58.000
But don't worry, says professional organizer and host of the declutter club podcast, Ingrid Yansen.

49
00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:04.000
The answer is to go slow, as she explains here to BBC Radio Force Woman's hour.

50
00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:20.000
You have to do decluttering slowly, but surely one drawer, one cupboard at a time, you can't go in all guns blazing, you can't go in, that's what we hear all the time. This weekend, I'm going to sort out my whole room of doom.

51
00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:30.000
And after two hours in, they will look around and go, what have I done, there's more chaos than there was before, because they've bitten off too much that they can chew.

52
00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:39.000
When it comes to decluttering your home, it's best to do things slowly, but surely, in a gradual but reliable way, which will achieve the result you want.

53
00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:50.000
It's a mistake to try to declutter everything all at once, with all guns blazing, an idiom meaning to do things dramatically with lots of energy and enthusiasm.

54
00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:58.000
After an hour or two of this, decluttering becomes physically and emotionally exhausting. You may have a bit enough more than you can chew.

55
00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:02.000
Another idiom, meaning to try doing something which is too difficult for you.

56
00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:08.000
So, if you want a declutter without stress, remember break the job down and go slow.

57
00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:12.000
Right, it's time to reveal the answer to my question, Georgie.

58
00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:17.000
I asked you how many Instagram posts you can currently find under the hashtag declutter.

59
00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:19.000
I said, B, 2.6 million.

60
00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:21.000
Well, you were correct, well done.

61
00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:22.000
Yay!

62
00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:27.000
Okay, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned in this episode about clutter.

63
00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:31.000
Things we buy which fill up our homes in an untidy disorganized way.

64
00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:36.000
When something has to work over time, it works extra hard using lots of energy.

65
00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:40.000
Work over time also often means work longer than your set hours.

66
00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:45.000
The adjective up lifted means feeling cheerful, happy and optimistic.

67
00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:52.000
If you do something slowly but surely, you do it in a gradual but reliable way which will achieve the result you want.

68
00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:57.000
The idiom with all guns blazing describes doing things with lots of energy and enthusiasm.

69
00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:03.000
And finally, if you bite off more than you can chew, you try to do something which is too difficult for you.

70
00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:11.000
Once again, our six minutes are up, but why not head over to our website, BBCLearningEnglish.com to try the quiz for this episode.

71
00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:13.000
Good luck decluttering and see you again soon.

72
00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:14.000
Goodbye.

73
00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:15.000
Bye.
